
In ISR, Next.js uses a time‑based cache with background revalidation. Pages are served from cache like static files, but they are regenerated periodically based on a revalidation interval—without blocking users or rebuilding the whole site.

🔹 The ISR Caching Model (Step‑by‑Step)
1️⃣ Build Time (Initial Cache)
	• At build time, Next.js generates the page using getStaticProps
	• The generated HTML is cached (CDN + server)
	• This cached page is served to all users

export async function getStaticProps() {
  return {
    props: { data },
    revalidate: 60 // seconds
  };
}
``

2️⃣ Request Before Revalidation Time
	• User requests the page
	• Next.js serves the page directly from cache
	• ✅ Fast response (static performance)
[User] → [CDN Cache] → [Static HTML]


3️⃣ Request After Revalidation Time
Once revalidate time has passed:
	• The first user still gets the old cached page
	• In the background, Next.js: 
		○ Re‑runs getStaticProps
		○ Generates a new version of the page
	• Cache is updated only after regeneration succeeds
✅ This is called stale‑while‑revalidate
User gets old page ✅
Background regeneration 🔄
Cache updated ✅

4️⃣ Subsequent Requests
	• New users now receive the updated cached page
✅ Zero downtime
✅ No blocking
✅ No full rebuild

🧠 Key Caching Principles in ISR
✅ Static Cache
	• Pages are cached like static assets
	• Served via CDN (extremely fast)
✅ Time‑Based Invalidation
	• Cache expires based on revalidate value
	• Not manual eviction
✅ Atomic Updates
	• Cache is replaced only if regeneration succeeds
	• If regeneration fails → old page stays
✅ Safe and resilient

⚠️ What ISR Caching Is Not
❌ Not per‑user caching
❌ Not real‑time updates
❌ Not request‑based like SSR
ISR is time‑based, not data‑change‑driven (unless you use on‑demand revalidation).

🔄 On‑Demand Revalidation (Advanced)
Instead of waiting for time:
res.revalidate('/products/123');
✅ Regenerates a specific page
✅ Triggered by CMS, webhook, admin action
Use this when:
	• Content editors publish updates
	• You want instant freshness without SSR

⚖️ ISR vs SSR Caching (Quick Contrast)
Aspect	ISR	SSR
Cache	✅ Yes (static)	❌ Usually no
Regeneration	Background	Every request
Performance	Very high	Medium
Freshness	Time‑based	Always fresh

🧠 Interview‑Ready 30‑Second Answer
	In ISR, pages are statically cached and served like static files. After the revalidation interval expires, Next.js serves the existing cached page while regenerating a new version in the background. Once regeneration succeeds, the cache is updated. This provides static performance with controlled freshness and avoids rebuilding the entire site.

